The main culprit Putin.
Moscow-based medical experts from Germany, France, and Sweden are in agreement: Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is Putin's largest critic and also the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, thanks to Navalny's survival, the relationship between Russia and Germany did not deteriorate.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel announced: Navalny is a "victim persecuted for freedom of speech."
In her eyes, this incident is extremely serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond.
She emphasized that the entire world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on the Russian authorities to launch an independent and transparent investigation.
The European Union and the United Kingdom also support this call.
If the investigation's result proves that the Russian government is the mastermind behind the event, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
Regardless of the circumstances, under the regulations of the Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, poisoning is prohibited.
This is not the first time Putin's government has used the nerve agent Novichok to target its political opponents.
In 2018, Russian former double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on the soil of the United Kingdom.
Both of them survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin has strongly denied both incidents.
The Kremlin's spokesman Dmitry Peskov firmly insists that "there is no evidence to blame the Russian government" over the Navalny case.
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service Director Sergei Naryshkin even said this is the behavior of Western intelligence agencies, attempting to implicate the Russian government's reputation.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly an attempt to justify the unjustifiable, but he also revealed a fact: the Navalny affair has caused more harm than good to Russia.
In the run-up to the upcoming elections, poisoning a prominent political opponent with a nerve agent developed by the former Soviet Union is inexcusable.
Especially at a time when people in neighboring Belarus are protesting the upcoming August elections, this timing is all the more intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny affair was particularly puzzling.
In carrying out the crime, should the Russian government not have planned a bit more meticulously?
If it was indeed the Russian government, as Germany claims, then this assassination attempt was also a failed operation.
Putin has been the Darth Vader of the international political scene, meddling in the US elections, inciting street protests in France, manipulating the UK's Brexit, and propping up Syrian President Bashar al-Assad.
As a former KGB operative, he was cunning, far-sighted, and devious.
That is why he failed to kill Skripal and Navalny.
Why could Navalny escape to Germany? And he was soon diagnosed with poisoning as well?
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, while the second phase of the Nord Stream pipeline project to Germany is facing cancellation.
This attempt was clearly not worth the cost.
In reality, this has only fueled public opposition to the Russia authorities' wrongdoing.
Even if it wasn't Putin's doing, the claim that Western intelligence agencies were behind it is even more far-fetched.
If such allegations are true, German and Swedish scientists would not have revealed the fact that Navalny was poisoned with the nerve agent Novichok.
More likely, it was a plot hatched by Putin's inner circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to remain silent before the election, or perhaps it was a backlash from Navalny's anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, though loyal, are foolish; they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, but only a few of those involved know the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts share similar characteristics: the attempted poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza is the coordinator of the Anti-Corruption Foundation's investigation committee.
The attempted poisoning of Mediazona editor-in-chief Peter Verzilov in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on Russia's judicial abuse of power.
The attempted poisoning of former KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko in 2006 also shares similar characteristics. Litvinenko was known for his frequent criticism of Russia's security agencies.
Just like the Navalny case, such poisoning attempts often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a columnist for the liberal newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a plane from Moscow to Beslan, although she survived, she was later shot dead in her apartment elevator two years later.
Just like Putin claimed, her death inflicted massive damage on Russia's government image.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
Regardless of whether Putin himself orchestrated it, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, amounting to a farce involving some shameless actors.
Navalny's death is the desired outcome for the Kremlin, and for his loyal dogs, the ultimate goal is to please their master Putin.
In Putin's inner circle, loyalty is the only goal.
Even if the poisoning attempt fails, they won't face punishment.
Because they are doing it all for the president's benefit.
Those who hope to find proof of poisoning may be disappointed.
Regardless of what is being said, the Kremlin is the mastermind behind it all.
Western countries must clearly condemn Russia, even if their own economy is affected, and impose sanctions on Russia.
Putin has created a system centered on himself.
All responsibility for what happened in Russia lies with him alone.
